   (3) 💬 ## Report
   (3) 💬 
   (3) 💬 **1. Existing tooltip pattern (buffer padding + input region masking)**
   (3) 💬 
   (3) 💬 - Padding constants & inflation math: `crates/core/shell/src/shell/component.rs:65-66` (`TOOLTIP_OVERLAY_WIDTH = 240`, `TOOLTIP_OVERLAY_HEIGHT = 80`); `tooltip_overlay_extra_for_content()` in `crates/core/shell/src/shell/component/rendering.rs:88-105` computes extra w/h added to the content box.
   (3) 💬 - Padding is folded into the parent surface's buffer/configure size elsewhere in `shell_component.rs` (e.g. line 544, 1620-1621 reference the same constants for surface sizing).
   (3) 💬 - Content-only rect exposed for input restriction: `ShellComponent::content_input_size()` — trait default at `crates/core/frontend/host/src/lib.rs:364`; real impl at `crates/core/shell/src/shell/component/shell_component.rs:1168-1174`, returning `self.last_surface_size` (the true content size, *not* the tooltip-inflated surface size).
   (3) 💬 - Consumer that actually restricts the Wayland input region: `crates/core/shell/src/shell/runtime/render.rs:778-802` inside `present_surface_target`, gated `if visible && is_parent`. It computes opaque region, then calls `content_input_size()` and if present calls `self.presentation_engine.update_input_region(&surface_id, Some(DamageRect{0,0,content_w,content_h}))`.
   (3) 💬 - Presentation-layer primitive: `crates/core/presentation/src/lib.rs:294-297` (`PresentationEngine::update_input_region`) forwards to `crates/core/presentation/src/wayland_surface/backend.rs:1262-1282` (`update_input_region`), which calls `wl_surface.set_input_region(...)` or `None` to reset to whole-surface input.
   (3) 💬 
   (3) 💬 **2. Popup (xdg_popup) buffer sizing today**
   (3) 💬 
   (3) 💬 - Popover content size is computed with zero padding: `crates/core/shell/src/shell/component/shell_component.rs:1793-1796` in `collect_child_surface_requests` — `content = (node.layout.width.ceil(), node.layout.height.ceil())`, the exact CSS-measured box, no shadow/overshoot allowance.
   (3) 💬 - That `content_size` flows straight through: surface width/height (`render.rs:512-513`), `PopupConfig.placement.size` (`render.rs:516-522`), and the paint buffer's physical dims in `paint_and_present_child_surface` (`render.rs:602-624`, using `width`/`height` params = `content_size.max(1)`).
   (3) 💬 - Paint itself (`paint_child_surface`, `shell_component.rs:1116-1150`) paints the node at `bounds` (its own layout position) into a buffer sized exactly to that content — no margin for `box-shadow`/glow/overshoot, so any shadow gets hard-clipped at the buffer edge.
   (3) 💬 - Input region: `present_surface_target`'s region-setting block (`render.rs:778`) is `is_parent`-only; child (`TargetRef::Child`) targets never call `update_input_region`, so popups fall back to whole-buffer input by default (`set_input_region(None)`). Currently harmless only because buffer == content; once padding is added, the whole padded buffer would become click-through-blocking dead space unless input region is explicitly restricted like the tooltip case.
   (3) 💬 - Buffer format: already `Argb8888` for all surfaces (`crates/core/presentation/src/wayland_surface/backend.rs:298`, `505`), i.e. popups already composite with alpha — the "needs an alpha buffer" note in the backlog is already satisfied; no format change needed.
   (3) 💬 
   (3) 💬 **3. Answer**
   (3) 💬 
   (3) 💬 Popup buffers are sized exactly to content — no shadow padding exists today, so `box-shadow`/glow on a promoted `<popover>` is currently clipped. No input region is set for child/popup targets at all (defaults to whole-surface input), which today is a no-op since buffer==content, but would become a real dead-zone bug the moment padding is added.
   (3) 💬 
   (3) 💬 **4. Scoping assessment**
   (3) 💬 
   (3) 💬 Well-scoped, buildable in one pass, and directly mirrors the parent/tooltip pattern — no new primitives needed (`update_input_region` already accepts arbitrary surface_id + rect). Concrete changes:
   (3) 💬 
   (3) 💬 - Add a popover-specific overlay-padding constant/helper analogous to `tooltip_overlay_extra_for_content` (or reuse a general one), likely based on max `box-shadow` blur+spread+offset rather than a fixed 240x80 — needs a way to read the popover node's shadow extent from `computed_style` (check if `mesh-core-elements` computed style already exposes box-shadow blur/spread; if not, a conservative fixed pad like the tooltip case is the minimal-risk fallback).
   (3) 💬 - In `collect_child_surface_requests` (`shell_component.rs:1793-1796`): inflate `content_size` by the padding, and record the *unpadded* content rect + offset (top-left inset) somewhere reachable per-child (e.g. a new field on `ChildSurfaceTarget`/`ChildSurfaceRuntime`, paralleling `last_surface_size` for parents).
   (3) 💬 - In `paint_child_surface` (`shell_component.rs:1116-1150`): offset painting by the padding inset so content still lands correctly inside the larger buffer (adjust the `-bounds.0, -bounds.1` translate by `+pad_x, +pad_y`).
   (3) 💬 - In `present_surface_target`'s region block (`render.rs:778`): extend the `is_parent` branch (or add a parallel child branch) to also call `update_input_region` for `TargetRef::Child` using the popover's unpadded content rect offset by the padding.
   (3) 💬 - No presentation-layer or alpha-format changes required — `update_input_region`/`set_input_region` and Argb8888 buffers already exist and are generic over surface id.
   (3) 💬 
   (3) 💬 Main open question before implementing: whether to size padding from actual computed `box-shadow` extent (correct, but requires checking if that's exposed) or reuse a fixed constant like the tooltip's 240x80 (simpler, matches "reuse the tooltip pattern" wording in the backlog item, but wastes buffer memory / may still clip large shadows).
